excerpt: Bustling covered market with stalls for produce, meat, clothing, souvenirs, snacks & fresh juices.
detail_description: Mercado Central de San Pedro is a lively covered market offering a variety of goods such as produce, meat, clothing, souvenirs, snacks, and fresh juices. Before visiting the market, you can explore the bohemian area of San Blas with its cobbled streets and Inca history. The neighborhood is known for its local artisans creating beautiful crafts sold at the Santurantikuy fair.
name: Mercado Central de San Pedro

excerpt: Inca ruins of a prominent 15th-century temple that once had walls & floors covered in pure gold.
detail_description: Qorikancha, also known as the 'Court of Gold,' is a significant Inca ruin located in Peru. It was originally built to honor the sun god and was adorned with pure gold, including walls, altars, and life-size statues of plants and animals. However, much of its wealth was looted during the Spanish conquest.
name: Qorikancha

excerpt: Built during the 16th & 17th centuries, this grand cathedral is filled with colonial paintings.
detail_description: Cusco Cathedral, constructed in the 16th and 17th centuries, is a grand structure adorned with colonial paintings. The cathedral was built over many years by various architects and masters, using stones from the Sacsayhuaman complex. It houses impressive pieces of art including 256 silver items and a silver monstrance embellished with pearls, rubies, amethysts, sapphires, and topazes.
name: Cusco Cathedral

detail_description: Villa San Blas, originally named Toqokachi, holds historical significance as the first parish established by the Spanish in Cusco. This district was once home to defeated Inca leaders and has since evolved into a charming area reflecting mestizo and colonial influences through its architecture and high-quality artesania. Today, it is renowned as the "barrio de los artesanos" or artisans' quarter, showcasing a rich cultural heritage.
name: Villa San Blas

detail_description: Plaza de Armas is a central location in Cusco, providing easy access to nearby attractions like San Blas, which is just a 15-20 minute walk away. To reach this iconic spot, visitors can stroll from the main square towards Triunfo Street, passing by The Rock of the 12 Angles before ascending Cuesta de San Blas.
name: Plaza de armas

detail_description: Nestled near Sacsayhuaman, the Cusco Planetarium offers a unique experience in the hills of Cusco. Unlike traditional planetariums, this one delves into the astronomical knowledge of the ancient Incas. The facility is run by Ana, Roberto, and their uncle Professor Garces, an experienced astronomy expert. The planetarium is designed with deep respect for Incan beliefs and features a dome camouflaged as a traditional local structure.
name: Cusco Planetarium
address: Fundo Llaullipata carretera a Sacsayhuaman Km2, Cusco 08002, Peru

excerpt: Buzzing central city square overlooked by a UNESCO-listed cathedral & Spanish colonial buildings.
detail_description: Plaza de Armas is a vibrant city square located in the heart of the bustling urban center. It is surrounded by well-preserved Spanish colonial buildings and is dominated by a UNESCO-listed cathedral. Historically, it was a significant site, once hosting the palace of the Inca, noble palaces, and important temples. Today, it remains a hub of activity and an essential stop for visitors looking to immerse themselves in the rich history and architecture of the area.
name: Pl. de Armas

excerpt: Ancient objects from 1250 B.C.–1532 A.D. on display in a 15th-century building with a cafe.
detail_description: Located in a 15th-century building, the Museo de Arte Precolombino (MAP) is a decade-old museum showcasing an extensive collection of artifacts from various Andean cultures and periods. The museum features interesting pre-Columbian artworks, Peruvian artifacts from the Cusco region, colorful pottery exhibits, detailed jewelry, and historical Inca treasures. The grand Spanish colonial mansion housing the museum includes its own ceremonial Inca courtyard. Visitors can easily appreciate the displays with multi-language labeling.
name: Museo de Arte Precolombino Larco

excerpt: Museum offering chocolate-making workshops along with guided tours, tastings & a cafe.
detail_description: ChocoMuseo, located near Plaza Regocijo in Cusco, is a unique museum dedicated to cocoa and chocolate. It offers guided tours, tastings, and workshops on chocolate making. The museum features a small exhibit at the back of the shop and an artisan chocolate factory that produces a wide variety of organic chocolates using grains grown in Cusco.
name: ChocoMuseo

excerpt: Cusco, a city in the Peruvian Andes, was once capital of the Inca Empire, and is now known for its archaeological remains and Spanish colonial architecture. Plaza de Armas is the central square in the old city, with arcades, carved wooden balconies and Incan wall ruins. The baroque Santo Domingo Convent was built on top of the Incan Temple of the Sun (Qoricancha), and has archaeological remains of Inca stonework.
detail_description: Cusco, located in the Peruvian Andes, was once the capital of the Inca Empire and is now renowned for its blend of archaeological sites and Spanish colonial architecture. The city's central square, Plaza de Armas, showcases a mix of arcades, intricately carved wooden balconies, and remnants of Incan walls. The baroque Santo Domingo Convent stands atop the Incan Temple of the Sun (Qoricancha), featuring preserved Inca stonework.
name: Cusco

excerpt: Placed in the wall of a once-Incan palace, this legendary stone is said to hold up the structure.
detail_description: The Twelve Angled Stone, located in Cusco, Peru, is a remarkable example of Inca masonry. This legendary stone is part of a wall built by the Inca Pachacuti and showcases their advanced stone-cutting techniques. What makes it special is its perfect finish and precisely interlocking surface with twelve angles that fit seamlessly without mortar.
name: Twelve Angled Stone

detail_description: Rainbow Mountain, also known as Montana de Siete Colores, is a must-see day trip from Cusco, Peru. This natural wonder features stunning rainbow-like marbling on its surface caused by mineral deposits. The site has gained immense popularity among travelers in recent years due to its Instagram fame and the revelation of its hidden beauty in 2013.
name: Rainbow Mountain
address: Av, Meson De La Estrella 136, Cusco, Peru

excerpt: Small pedestrian plaza in an artists' community with benches, a fountain, a gallery & a temple.
detail_description: Plazoleta de San Blas is a charming pedestrian plaza nestled in an artistic neighborhood. The plaza features inviting benches, a tranquil fountain, an art gallery, and a quaint temple. It's a perfect spot to soak up the local atmosphere and relax. While exploring the San Blas neighborhood, visitors can also stop by the Peru Hop office located nearby to discover exciting activities in Cusco and its surroundings.
name: Plazoleta de San Blas

detail_description: Plaza San Blas is located in Cusco's artisan quarter and is home to a variety of workshops and galleries such as Galeria Arte Olave and Museo Taller Hilario Mendivil, offering an array of striking artifacts, sculptures, religious images, ceramics, and earthenware. The plaza features a small artificial waterfall and picturesque stairs leading to a charming spot for photos with the city and mountains in the background.
name: Plaza San Blas
address: F2MG+W7Q, Cuesta de San Blas, Cusco 08003, Peru

excerpt: Completed in 1765, this stone church features a stunning interior covered in gold leaf.
detail_description: The Church of the Society of Jesus, completed in 1765, is a stunning stone church with a baroque-style interior covered in gold leaf. Situated on the site of the ancient Amarucancha, palace of Inca Huayna Capac, it features Inca walls as foundations and has a Latin cross design on the floor.
name: Church of the Society of Jesus
address: Plaza de Armas Cusco S/N, Cusco 08001, Peru

excerpt: Folksy collection of Inca art, artifacts & architecture in a modest, old-fashioned environment.
detail_description: The Inka Museum, located in the city of Cusco, offers a charming collection of Inca art, artifacts, and architecture within an old-fashioned setting. The museum is situated on the former palace of Huascar, an Inca emperor. Over time, the property changed hands among various owners including Spanish conquistadors and local families. Visiting this gem allows you to delve into the rich history of the Inca civilization from its origins to its eventual conquest by the Spanish.
name: Inka Museum

excerpt: Circa-1945, 26-foot Christ statue on a hill, a popular destination for city & night views.
detail_description: Mirador desde el Cristo Blanco is a popular destination in Cusco, featuring a 26-foot Christ statue on a hill. The statue was donated by the Arab-Palestinian community and built in 1945 by local sculptor Francisco Olazo. To reach the mirador, visitors can take a steep hike from the main square through Hatunrumiyoc street and atoqsayquchi street.
name: Mirador desde el Cristo Blanco

detail_description: The Mirador de San Cristobal offers a breathtaking panoramic view of Cusco, stretching from north to south. From this vantage point, visitors can admire the Temple of San Cristobal, known for its Baroque style and rich history dating back to 1546. The viewpoint also provides a glimpse of Collcampata, the oldest Inca palace, with its ancient stone walls and raised altars.
name: Mirador de Sán Cristobal
address: Plaza San Cristobal, Don Bosco, Cusco 08002, Peru

detail_description: Cristo Blanco is an 8-meter tall white statue of Jesus located in Cusco, Peru. It can be easily accessed from the direction of Saqsaywaman to the west or Q'enco to the east. The viewpoint offers a stunning perspective of the city and is often compared to Rio's Cristo Redentor.
name: Cristo Blanco

detail_description: Shopping Center 'El Sol' in Cusco is a must-visit for those looking to bring home souvenirs and textiles from Peru. Located along the streets like Calles Plateros and Triunfo leading to Plaza Armas, this small but interesting shopping center offers a variety of items. Visitors can find computer technical services, delicious snacks at Mrs. CHEPITA's, and a jewelry store with good prices.
name: Shopping Center "El Sol"

detail_description: La Catedral is a cozy restaurant that offers a delicious lunch menu with three options from Monday to Saturday at an affordable price. In the evenings, they serve sausages, Broaster chicken, and other tasty choices. Payment is accepted in cash or through Yape, as credit cards are not an option. While parking on-site is unavailable, there's space on the adjacent street for convenience.
name: La catedral
address: F2J7+86W, C. Nueva Alta, Cusco 08002, Peru

excerpt: Inca complex surrounded by walls that were made by fitting stones tightly together without mortar.
detail_description: Saqsaywaman is an awe-inspiring archaeological site located just north of Cusco, Peru. This ancient Inca fortress is renowned for its impressive stone walls, constructed with remarkable precision and without the use of mortar. The site features a complex layout that includes residential areas, temples, roads, and aqueducts, showcasing the advanced engineering prowess of the Incas.
name: Saqsaywaman

excerpt: Spanish church & convent built on top of & with materials from the sacred Inca temple Qorikancha.
detail_description: The Church and Convent of Santo Domingo of Guzmán is a historic site in Peru, built on the sacred Inca temple Qorikancha. The space was given to the Dominican order during Spanish colonization, leading to the construction of the convent in 1534. The site showcases a fusion of Inca walls and colonial architecture, with parts of the Inca temple now serving as a museum displaying rooms where worship to various Incan deities took place.
name: Church and Convent of Santo Domingo of Guzmán

excerpt: Mid-1500s church featuring an intricate wood pulpit carved in the Spanish Churrigueresque style.
detail_description: Templo del San Blas, a church in Cusco, is renowned for its exquisite artistry and unique architecture. The intricately carved pulpit, believed to be the finest in the world, showcases a fusion of indigenous and colonial artistic traditions. Located in the artisan quarter of San Blas neighborhood, this cultural gem stands on the site of an Incan temple dedicated to the god of thunder and lightning.
name: Templo del San Blas

excerpt: Incan art & excavated finds, plus colonial paintings & Jesuit sculptures in a former writer's home.
detail_description: Housed in the former residence of Inca Garcilaso de la Vega Chimpu Ocllo, a prominent colonial poet and historian with both Spanish and Inca heritage, the Regional Historical Museum of Cusco offers a captivating journey through Peru's diverse historical periods. The museum showcases an array of paleontological and archaeological artifacts dating back to prehistoric eras, as well as colonial paintings, Jesuit sculptures, and excavated finds.
name: Regional Historical Museum of Cusco

detail_description: Plaza de San Blas, located in the charming San Blas neighborhood of Cusco, offers some of the most breathtaking views in the city. This vibrant area is dotted with trendy restaurants, cozy cafes, and lively bars, making it a popular spot for both locals and tourists. The plaza and its surroundings are perfect for leisurely strolls while taking in the picturesque scenery and enjoying the bustling atmosphere.
name: Plaza de San Blas

detail_description: The Inca Trail is a life-changing experience, considered one of the best walks globally, offering breathtaking landscapes with mountains, rivers, and Inca sites. It requires good physical condition but promises a wonderful adventure. For those seeking an alternative to walking the entire trail, options like the 3 Day or 2 Day Inca Trail Tours are available. Families can also enjoy this trek with children by taking strategic stops and teaching them about the history of the trail while exploring ancient ruins.
name: Inca Trail

detail_description: The Sapantiana Aqueduct, a hidden gem near Cusco's Plaza de Armas, is a historical marvel with three levels of arches resembling a bridge over the Saphi River. Dating back to 1565, it was built during the Peruvian colonial period to supply water to the city center. Despite being discovered in mid-2020, this aqueduct has been an integral part of Cusco for centuries and offers visitors a glimpse into Inca culture and infrastructure.
name: Sapantiana Aqueduct
address: Plazoleta de San Blas, Cusco 08000, Peru

detail_description: The Inti Raymi Festival is a grand celebration in Cusco, Peru, dedicated to the Inca Sun god. It features over 300 local dancers and actors dressed in traditional Inca attire, showcasing a reenactment of ancient Inca rituals. This festival was revived by Cusco scholars in 1944 and has become a focal point for June celebrations in the city.
name: Inti Raymi Festival

detail_description: Rainbow Mountain, once a hidden gem but now a popular spot thanks to social media, is easily accessible as a day trip from Cusco. Unlike typical itineraries, this tour allows you to escape the crowds and even enjoy some extra sleep. Find out more about the one-day Rainbow Mountain excursion for a unique experience.
name: Quechua Road Trips

excerpt: Small musuem featuring a permanent collection of contemporary Peruvian tapestries, plus exhibitions.
detail_description: Museo Maximo Laura in Cusco is a small museum that showcases the contemporary Peruvian tapestries of master artisan Maximo Laura. The museum's two floors are adorned with stunning, vibrant handwoven tapestries that reimagine traditional designs with breathtaking colors and intricate details. Visitors can witness artisans at work, showcasing deep-rooted skills honed over generations.
name: Museo Maximo Laura

excerpt: Lively urban gathering place offering colonial arcades, a cathedral, gardens & a central fountain.
detail_description: Plaza Mayor de Cusco, also known as Plaza de Armas, is a vibrant urban hub featuring colonial arcades, a cathedral, gardens, and a central fountain. It serves as the starting point for exploring major Cusco attractions such as Qoricancha and La Catedral. Visitors can immerse themselves in the city's culture by browsing through various shops and markets along the way. The square also hosts religious and cultural celebrations with music and dancing filling the streets.
name: Plaza de Armas de Cusco

excerpt: Ancient, elaborate Catholic church & monastery with fountains, murals & statuary.
detail_description: Basilica Menor de la Merced is an ancient Catholic church and monastery in Cusco, originally constructed in the 16th century. The Andean Baroque style church suffered damage from earthquakes over the years but has been rebuilt. It houses the remains of historical figures like Gonzalo Pizarro and Francisco de Carbajal.
name: Basilica Menor de la Merced

excerpt: Colonial house turned museum for archaeological finds from Machu Picchu, excavation photos & videos.
detail_description: Housed in an 18th-century colonial building, Museo Casa Concha is a museum that boasts the world's most extensive collection of Inca artifacts from Machu Picchu. The museum showcases nearly 400 archaeological pieces, including excavation photos and videos, offering visitors a comprehensive insight into the lifestyle and craftsmanship of the Incas. The collection includes findings by Hiram Bingham, the American explorer who first revealed the existence of the ancient Incan citadel.
name: Museo Casa Concha
address: F2MF+365, Sta. Catalina Ancha, Cusco 08002, Peru

detail_description: Pachapapa is a charming restaurant located in Cusco, celebrated for its rustic atmosphere and traditional Andean decor. The courtyard offers a delightful dining experience with parasols and greenery during the day, while evenings are enlivened by candlelight and local musicians. The menu features meat-oriented dishes such as cuy chactado, kankacho, and pizzas topped with local ingredients like smoked trout.
name: Pachapapa

excerpt: Centuries-old cobbled square surrounded by colonial buildings like the Chapel San Antonio Abad.
detail_description: Nazarenas is a charming centuries-old cobbled square nestled among colonial buildings, including the Chapel San Antonio Abad. Located near Plaza de Armas and towards San Blas, this area offers unique spots like Fallen Angel in Plaza Nazarenas for its funky decor and Uchu Steakhouse for exceptional carne roja. Another popular choice nearby is Cicciolina on Calle Triunfo, making it a must-visit destination for food enthusiasts.
name: Nazarenas

excerpt: This small museum features educational exhibits on coca, plus a gift shop with an array of products.
detail_description: The Coca Museum is a small museum that offers educational exhibits on the coca plant, along with a gift shop selling various coca products. It provides insight into the Andean tradition of coca and its historical significance in Peruvian culture, showcasing its uses for medicinal and recreational purposes. The museum's exhibits are presented in both English and Spanish, covering the history of coca use from ancient Inca times to modern-day contexts such as narco wars.
name: Coca Museum
address: Cta. de San Blas 618 618, Cusco 08003, Peru

detail_description: The Arco de Santa Clara is a picturesque spot that's worth capturing on camera, although you may need to be patient for a gap in the traffic. It's an ideal place to pause and take in the surroundings before continuing your journey.
name: Arco de Santa Clara

detail_description: Kusicancha, located in Cusco, is a historic residential neighborhood with homes facing courtyards. When the Spanish arrived, many of these neighborhoods were destroyed or repurposed for colonial structures. Part of Kusicancha has been restored to give visitors a glimpse into how Cusco looked during Inca rule. Adjacent to Qoricancha and part of the same temple complex, Kusicancha offers foundational Incan ruins and a tranquil atmosphere away from the crowds.
name: Kusicancha

detail_description: Located in the basement of the Boleto Turistico del Cusco office on Avenida El Sol, Museo de Arte Popular houses a diverse collection of ceramics, photographs, paintings, and sculptures. The museum features works by renowned Peruvian artists like Edilberto Merida, Hilario Mendivil, and Santiago Rojas. Managed by the Instituto Americano de Arte, it offers a unique insight into local artistry.
name: Museo de Arte Popular

detail_description: Monasterio de Santa Catalina de Nuestra Señora de Los Remedios, originally built on an Inca site known as AcllaWasi, was established in 1605 by the Dominican nuns. The convent suffered damage during the 1650 earthquake and underwent reconstruction, completing in 1669. Notably, it welcomed Melchora Clara Coya, a descendant of Huayna Capac, as one of its first aspirants to religious life.
name: Monasterio de Santa Catalina de Nuestra Señora de Los Remedios

detail_description: The Temple of the Moon, also known as Huaca de la Luna, is situated near Trujillo in Northern Peru. It was part of the ancient city of Huacas de Moche and alongside the Temple of the Sun. The remnants between these structures reveal a densely populated community with residential areas, workshops, and religious buildings. The site features finely finished floors and painted walls.
name: Temple of the Moon

detail_description: Cuyeria Sabor Moqueguano is a local eatery in Cusco that specializes in serving guinea pig, a traditional Inca dish and popular delicacy in Peru. The restaurant offers various preparations of cuy, such as Cuy al Horno (baked guinea pig) and Cuy Chactado (fried guinea pig). This spot is known for its authentic and non-touristy ambiance, making it a great place to experience traditional Peruvian cuisine.
name: Cuyeria Sabor Moqueguano

detail_description: Museo del Pisco in Cusco is not your typical museum, but rather a popular bar that has been a favorite among nightlife enthusiasts for nearly a decade. Housed in a restored colonial building with historical significance, this three-level bar offers an extensive selection of Peruvian piscos, including rare bottles from cult producers. The walls are adorned with informative displays about pisco's history and culture, making it an educational experience as well.
name: MUSEO DEL PISCO - CUSCO

detail_description: The Boleto Turístico Cusco is a must-have for anyone planning to explore the archaeological wonders of Peru's Sacred Valley. Priced at S/130 for a 10-day pass, this ticket grants access to 16 Inca ruins and museums in Cusco, including popular sites like Ollantaytambo, Moray, and Chinchero. For students with valid IDs, the cost is reduced to S/70.
name: Boleto Turístico Cusco

detail_description: Inti Raymi is a renowned restaurant in Cusco, located within the 5-star Palacio del Inka hotel. It offers a luxurious and romantic fine dining experience with a focus on Peruvian and international cuisine. Another popular dining spot is the INKAGRILL at Plaza de Armas, known for its fusion of Peruvian and international flavors. In June, Cusco hosts various celebrations, with Inti Raymi being the most prominent.
name: Inti Raymi

detail_description: Located in the heart of Cusco, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the Municipality of Cusco, also known as MUSAC, was established in 1995 and is housed within the historic Cabildo Palace. The museum's collection boasts over 300 artworks by both local and international artists, with a focus on contemporary art from the Andean region.
name: Museum of Contemporary Art of the Municipality of Cusco

detail_description: Que Chicha Restaurant, in honor of the ancient corn beer of the Incas, is one of the most famous places to enjoy regional food in Cusco.
name: Que Chicha Restaurante

detail_description: Loreto is a charming street located just a short stroll from Plaza de Armas. Strolling along this spacious yet narrow thoroughfare, visitors are flanked by impressive Incan walls constructed from intricately carved stones. The remarkable preservation of these massive walls offers an awe-inspiring glimpse into ancient construction techniques.
name: Loreto
